to both Dene and non-Dene readers alike. The methodology of the book is one of "participatory action research," in which the community itself owned and directed the research, training, and outcomes. By exposing the very different values and legal systems of the Dene and non-Dene, this book sets the framework for the possibility of a Dene-controlled and culturally appropriate justice system. The book will be of value to those interested in native self-government, constitutional rights, and aboriginal law, as well as to all those involved with First Nations peoples.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCustomary lawzNorthwest TerritorieszLac La Martre. 0aDogrib IndiansxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aDogrib IndiansxSocial life and customs. 0aJustice, Administration ofzNorthwest TerritorieszLac La Martre. 7aLAW / Indigenous Peoples.2bisacsh  aCanadian indigenous justice.  aCanadian justice system.  aaboriginal justice.  aculturally appropriate justice.  adene justice.  adene law.  adene legal system.  adene traditional justice.  adogrib justice.  adogrib law.  adogrib traditional justice.  aelder research.  aindigenous justice program.  aindigenous justice systems.  aindigenous justice.  aindigenous knowledge.  aindigenous law.  aindigenous legal systems.  aoral research.  aparticipatory action research.  aparticipatory research.  atraditional justice.  atraditional knowledge.  atraditional law.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781552383285?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781552383285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781552383285/